Cell.Data: A record of a healthcare consumer’s privacy policy, which is in accordance with governing jurisdictional and organization privacy policies that grant or withhold consent:

• To one or more identified entities in a defined role • To perform one or more operations (e.g. collect, access, use, disclose, amend, or delete) • On an instance or type of individually identifiable health information [IIHI] • For a purpose such as treatment, payment, operations, research, public health, quality measures, health status evaluation by third parties, or marketing • Under certain conditions, e.g. when unconscious • For specified time period, e.g. effective and expiration dates • In certain context, e.g. in an emergency A consent directive is an instance of governing jurisdictional and organization privacy policies, which may or may not be backed up by a signed document (paper or electronic).

In the context of a consent, the topic is the matter under consideration in regards to which specific rights, privileges, obligations, restrictions, and prohibitions are binding on any grantor and grantee parties upon the execution of the consent. Given the wide range of consent topics, implementers need to be cognizant of the business use case for which they are designing a FHIR Consent, and narrowly specify the topic being represented with respect to the Consent.type and any specializing Consent.subtype. The same topic, e.g., an asset such as a good or service, such as a real property, medical supply, insurance, information, a procedure or employment, or a manner of conduct, such adherence to a privacy, trust, or security policy, may be the topic of multiple types of consents. One way to determine the Consent.topic is to answer the question: “What is the object of negotiation?” Answer: The Consent.topic, which may be described with more detail in the [0..*]Consent.valuedItem @ [0..1] Consent.valuedItem.entity[x] Definition: Specific type of Consent Valued Item that may be priced. CodeableConcept|Reference(Any) Consent.topic is “the what” that a grantor is exchanging with a grantee in return for some benefit. Consent.topic is “the what” to which any Consent.action is being applied for any stipulated Consent.action.reason. AConsent.topic is “the what” governed by the execution of the consent to which any party’s rights, privileges, obligations, restrictions, and prohibitions apply.

The Consent.topic may be an application for or offer of a policy or service (e.g., uri to a consent directive form or a health insurance policy), which becomes the Consent once accepted by both the grantor and grantee. The Consent Resource may function simply as the computable representation of the executed consent, which may be the attached to the Consent Resource as the “binding” or as the “friendly” electronic form. For example, a Consent Resource may be automatically populated with the values expressed in a related QuestionnaireResponse. However, the Consent Resource may be considered the legally binding consent if it is the only “executed” form of this consent, and includes the signatures as *The Consent Resource may function as the computable representation of an application or offer in a pre-executed Consent if the grantor has not entered any values. In this case, it is populated with values in a “legal” form of the application or offer or by the values in an associated Questionnaire. If the grantor has filled in the legal form or the associated Questionnaire Response, then these values are used to populate a pre-executed Consent Resource. If the Consent.topic is considered an application or offer, then the policy is often required to be attached as the “legal” basis for the application to ensure “informed consent” to the consent, and that any discrepancy between the application and the policy are interpreted against the policy. Implementers should check organizational and jurisdictional policies to determine the relationship among multiple representations of a consent pre- and post-execution.
The target entity impacted by or of interest to parties to the agreement.

The Consent.subject is an entity that has some role with respect to the Consent.topic and Consent.topic.term, which is of focal interest to the parties to the consent and likely impacted in a significant way by the Consent.action/Consent.action.reason and the Consent.term.action/Consent.action.reason. In many cases, the Consent.subject is a Consent.signer if the subject is an adult; has a legal interest in the consent; and incompetent to participate in the consent agreement.

An actor taking a role in an activity for which it can be assigned some degree of responsibility for the activity taking place.
An agent can be a person, an organization, software, device, or other entities that may be ascribed responsibility.

Several agents may be associated (i.e. has some responsibility for an activity) with an activity and vice-versa. For example, in cases of actions initiated by one user for other users, or in events that involve more than one user, hardware device, software, or system process. However, only one user may be the initiator/requestor for the event.
